Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Trim and thinly slice @button mushrooms{4%ounce}(trimmed and thinly sliced) (skip if your mushrooms are pre-sliced!). Halve @potato buns{2}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%teaspoon} and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and crisp, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add mushrooms and cook, stirring, until lightly browned and softened, ~{3-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir in half the @mushroom stock concentrate{1} (you'll use the rest in the next step) and @water{1%tablespoon}. Cook, stirring, until mushrooms are coated, ~{30%seconds}.

Turn off heat; transfer mushrooms to a #small bowl{}. Wipe out pan.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce} and remaining mushroom stock concentrate. Season with salt and pepper. Form mixture into two patties, each slightly wider than a burger bun (four patties for 4).

Heat a large drizzle of olive oil in pan used for mushrooms over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top each patty with @Swiss cheese{2%slices}. Cover pan until cheese melts.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

While patties cook, toast buns in a #pan{} until golden.

In a second small bowl, combine @sour cream{3%tablespoon} and @honey Dijon dressing{1.5%ounce}. Season with salt and pepper.

Spread bottom buns with as much sauce as you like. Top with patties, mushrooms, and top buns.

Divide burgers and potato wedges between plates. Serve with any remaining sauce on the side for dipping.